project.name: Zeppelin data analytics demo
project.description: Real-time IoT data analytics and visualization with Kaa, Apache Cassandra, and Apache Zeppelin
project.details:
This sample Kaa application generates power measurements and uploads them to Cassandra for further processing. In the next step, by using Zeppelin notebook integrated with Cassandra, the user will be able to execute analytics queries against the collected data and generate insightful charts and reports.

This application can be used as a prototype for building a production-grade Kaa-based IoT application that collects any kind of sensor data on endpoints and uploads it into the preferred analytics platform.

Please review the webinar below for hands-on experience based on an earlier version of the Kaa platform.


About Kaa, Cassandra and Zeppelin

Kaa is open-source IoT middleware platform for building, managing, and integrating connected products with the Internet of Things. Kaa offers production-ready IoT features that allow developers to create IoT applications for smart products and connected devices in a very condensed timeframe.

The Apache Cassandra database is is an open source distributed database management system designed to handle large amounts of data across many commodity servers, providing high availability with no single point of failure. Linear scalability and proven fault-tolerance on commodity hardware or cloud infrastructure make it the perfect platform for mission-critical data.

The Apache Zeppelin is a web-based notebook that enables interactive data analytics. You can make beautiful data-driven, interactive and collaborative documents with SQL, Scala and virtually any other language or data-processing-backend.

Installation

1. Download the source code by clicking the "Source" button on the left and unpack the downloaded archive.
2. Connect to your Kaa Sandbox via ssh: 
$ ssh kaa@YOUR-SANDBOX-IP
password: kaa
3. Download Apache Zeppelin from the official page and install it to your Sandbox. Execute following commands: 
$ cd /opt
$ sudo wget http://www.eu.apache.org/dist/incubator/zeppelin/0.5.6-incubating/zeppelin-0.5.6-incubating-bin-all.tgz
$ sudo tar -xzvf zeppelin-0.5.6-incubating-bin-all.tgz
$ sudo ln -s /opt/zeppelin-0.5.6-incubating-bin-all /opt/zeppelin
$ cd ./zeppelin/conf
$ sudo cp ./zeppelin-env.sh.template  ./zeppelin-env.sh
4. Change the default Zeppelin port if needed. (In case of the free port 8080, you can skip this step). Add line: 
export ZEPPELIN_PORT=7080
into the zeppelin-env.sh file.
5. Start Zeppelin. 
$ sudo /opt/zeppelin/bin/zeppelin-daemon.sh start
6. Configure Cassandra log appenders.
Navigate to the Kaa server administrative interface by clicking the "Administrative console" link at the top of the Sandbox window. Log in as a tenant developer (devuser / devuser123), and navigate to the "Zeppelin data analytics demo" application, then select "Log appenders". From here you can manage two log appenders "Panel per row appender" and "Zone per row appender". Update appenders according to your Cassandra cluster configuration. Make sure that version of your Cassandra cluster is not higher than 2.2 which Cassandra Zeppelin interpreter currently supports.
7. On your host PC go to the JZeppelinDataAnalyticsDemo/lib folder and rename kaa-java-ep-sdk-.jar to the kaa-java-ep-sdk.jar.
8. Go to the JZeppelinDataAnalyticsDemo folder and start Zeppelin data analytics demo by executing command: 
$ mvn clean install exec:java
9. Navigate to the Zeppelin by entering in your browser: 
YOUR-SANDBOX-IP:7080/#/
Then configure the Cassandra Zeppelin interpreter according to your Cassandra cluster configuration. More information about Apache Zeppelin you can find on site. On the screens below you can see our custom notebook:
Panel power:
%cassandra select zone_id, panel_id, power as "power, MW", timeFormat(timestamp) as time from logs.zone_per_row where zone_id={{zone_id='Sierra'}} and timestamp > logs.timeDelta(toUnixTimestamp(now()), 60000) ORDER BY timestamp ASC;

Zone power:
%cassandra select zone_id, panel_id, power as "power, MW", timeFormat(timestamp) as time from logs.panel_per_row where zone_id={{zone_id='Sierra'}} and panel_id={{panel_id='Panel 0'}} and timestamp > logs.timeDelta(toUnixTimestamp(now()), 60000) ORDER BY timestamp ASC;


For more details, please refer to our webinar video embeded above "Real-time IoT data analytics and visualization with Kaa, Apache Cassandra, and Apache Zeppelin".
